The evidence consistently identifies low rather than high resistance patterns in normal carotid arteries—specifically noting low-resistance flow in the internal carotid artery (ICA), with monophasic waveforms lacking reverse flow. Increased pulsatility and resistance indexes are typically associated with pathology like atherosclerosis or obstruction, not normative findings. Obesity-related vascular stress is not directly tied to elevated carotid resistance in youth, nor is it established as an early marker. Therefore, increased resistance indexes are unlikely to represent early vascular abnormalities in this group.

